<font color="#FF0000">PAUSE AND CONSIDER</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul 26  9:05:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
You *all* are wrong to call each other names.<br><br>
Some of us are able to see shades of gray. Some see only in black and white.<br><br>
I served in Vietnam and led men. I am a decorated veteran. The six men in my platoon were decorated. We found out what &quot;standing our ground&quot; meant on June 5 1970 when many enemy mortar rounds and RPGs landed directly on our 2 mortar positions. Our only job initially, during night attacks, was to provide illumination so that the rifle platoons could see. It would be a &quot;stretch&quot; to say that many of the enemy died trying to breech our defenses. Instead, they couldn't even get the ground assault started. They retreated and left many rpg rounds and chicom grenades behind. I did my job. Not out of Patriotism or a &quot;cause&quot;. Rather, we hung in there because our lives and the lives of our buds depended on us all doing our jobs. Cook, I wish that I could see our cause as being &quot;just&quot;. I just don't. <br><br>
Allow me to shed some &quot;light&quot; once again, by repeating that you guys are dead wrong to be conducting yourselves this way. Doc, Ed, and Cook, check out this site and see how many times I had referred to others as being &quot;wrong&quot;.<br><br>
I am in the middle of planning a trip back to Vietnam with my wife and youngest son. I have this pipe dream of &quot;righting some wrongs&quot;. It's just the way that I am.<br><br>
I told a lady yesterday of my planned trip to VN. Immediately, the subject was CHANGED to her recent trip to New Orleans! Vietnam was not mentioned again during that conversation. I think it is safe to say that each and every Vietnam vet has experienced this same thing. <br><br>
The ones with the most questions about my war experience were not the war's &quot;supporters&quot;. The most curious and conversant about my experience were those who opposed it out of CONSCIENCE. Stereotyping and judging others is a form of &quot;playing God&quot;. As a Vietnam Vet, I can positively say that we all know the destruction of stereotyping.<br><br>
Erecting barriers of distrust and misunderstanding is not what dialogue should entail - at least not to those who make claims of desiring &quot;truth&quot;.<br><br>
The greatest and most important compensation of being a Veteran is not in being recognized as a hero. The compensation is in the knowing that we have the good fortune to live in a great country. By God's grace alone we were spared having our names engraved on a wall.<br><br>
The question remains: what are we doing about it?
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


